column2: Lightweight Web Worker API implementation with native threads

column5:
Merge pull request #194 from mmig/feature_importScripts-path-resolving

#192 importScripts: resolve relative path against WebWorker location

importScripts: resolve relative path against WebWorker location instead of Current Working Directory

 * store location of WebWorker script as __filename
 * on importScripts: if imported path is no absolute URL, resolve against path of WebWorker's __filename

 * special treatment of non-URL paths (i.e. system file paths): "guess" (heuristic) if system file path is absolute
   * store Current Working Directory in WebWorker instance as __cwd
   * if system path is sub path to __cwd, treat as absolute (i.e. if __cwd is prefix of the path)
   * introduce escape character '!': if path starts with '!', treat the path as absolute path (i.e. do not resolve against WebWorker script location)

Test22 - don't run forever

1. Don't run forever.

Problem: It was creating an infinite number of threads.
Solution: Create 1000 threads, enough to prove the point.

2. Actually print ongoing updates.

Problem: It was using process.nextTick to queue the next set of threads.
         On recent versions of Node this means display() will never get to run.

Solution: Switch to setTimeout(again, 0).

Merge pull request #127 from davisjam/TweakREADME

DOCS Tweak description of threadPool.on

DOCS Tweak description of threadPool.on

Previous description:
"...is like `thread.on()`, registers listeners for events from any of the threads in the pool."

Problem:
This makes it sound like the threads will emit events and that the
threadPool will listen for them.

The actual behavior is to call thread.on() for each thread in the pool.

Solution:
Update the README to reflect this.

Merge pull request #2 from uber/master

Fix Linux compilation issue
* Clarify we use @message because LiveScript autodeclares the variable.
* Remove self.* prefix from docs and examples.
* Allow setting "onmessage = " directly in the worker.
* Windows portability; open in binary mode
* Windows support added; tested on Node.js 0.9.3+.

* Finish pthread_* => uv_* porting.

  Now compiles on Win32, although doesn't yet work properly.
* Node 0.9.x support is currently broken, so fix node on 0.8.x.
* README: Use the 5-threads web worker example

* Change typedefs to uv_*.

  Note that uv_cond_* is only supported by node 0.9.3+, so
  Windows support is not yet possible with node 0.8.x --
  but possibly in node 0.10.x.
* Style agreement between and fiveThreads.ls and multiThreadEvented.ls
* Port the fiveThreads example to Worker + LiveScript
* 0.2.4: Switch to BSON instead of JSON for message serialization.
* We now require Node.js 0.8.0 with gypfile
* 0.2.3: Add SunOS to supported OSs; tested on Linux.

* Release 0.2.1.

  Allow JSON-encodable data structures in postMessage/onmessage.

* Implement self.close().

* Include MDN example in README.

* Basic implementation of W3C Web Worker API.

  See test.ls for an example; note that this is an extension:

    new Worker(function(){
        ... // Evaluates the function body into the worker
    })

  The standard file-based API still works, of course:

    new Worker("worker.js")

* Note MIT license for threads_a_gogo.

* Also waive my copyright under CC0.
* Massive renaming from threads_a_gogo to WebWorkerThreads.
